<p>The pattern is familiar. The first raise justifies a better apartment. The next supports a newer car. Then come more frequent trips, upgraded restaurants, premium subscriptions, a larger wedding budget, perhaps a house purchase sized to the new salary rather than to long-term goals. None of these decisions feels reckless because each is framed in monthly terms: “It’s only another $400 here, $700 there.”</p>
